No matter if your Gear VR project is a sitting or standing experience, the manner in which the user's camera is set up will be the same. In the following How - To we will go over how up the UE4 camera for use with the Gear VR HMD.


## Project & Basic Camera Setup for a Gear VR Experience 

Below you will find instructions on project setup requirements as well as how to create the needed Pawn Blueprints for Gear VR.

1. First, create a new UE4 project with the following settings and once the setting has been input, press the **Create Project** button to create the project.

    * Blueprint 
    * Blank Project
    * Mobile / Tablet
    * Scalable 3D or 2D
    * No Starter Content
    * Location for the project to be saved
    * Name for the project

    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_00.png)(w:555)](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_00.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. Once the project loads, tight-click in the **Content Browser** and from the displayed menu, go to the **Create Basic Asset** section and select the **Blueprint Class** option.

    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](Platforms\Oculus\HowTo\StandingCamera\HT_Rift_Camera_Setup_01.png)(w:150)](Platforms\Oculus\HowTo\StandingCamera\HT_Rift_Camera_Setup_01.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. From the **Pick Parent Class** window, select the **Pawn** option and then give it a name of **GearVR_Pawn**.

    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_01.png)(w:555)](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_01.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. Open up the GearVR_Pawn Blueprint and go to the **Component** section of the **Viewport** tab. Using the **Add Component** button add the following two components with the following names and also make sure that the VRCamera is a child of the VRCameraRoot.
    
    * Scene - VRCameraRoot
    * Camera - VRCamera

    ![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_02.png)

    [region:note]
    No matter what VR HMD you are using, this is the Epic recommend way to set up a VR camera as it allows you to offset the position of the camera without having to move the actual camera.
    [/region]

Now that a basic Blueprint for the VR Player has been created, in the next section, we will go through setting up this Blueprint to be used with Gear VR.

## Camera Setup for Gear VR Experience 

Below you will find instructions on how to setup your camera for a Gear VR experience.


1. First, open up the **GearVR_Pawn** Blueprint and in the **Event Graph** drag off the **Event Begin Play** node to show the Executable Actions list and search for the **Set Tracking Origin** node, clicking on it to add it to the Event Graph.

    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](Platforms\Oculus\HowTo\StandingCamera\HT_Rift_Camera_Setup_09.png)(w:555)](Platforms\Oculus\HowTo\StandingCamera\HT_Rift_Camera_Setup_09.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. Make sure the **Origin** of the Set Tracking Origin node is set to **Eye Level**.
    
    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](Platforms\Oculus\HowTo\StandingCamera\HT_Rift_Camera_Setup_10.png)(w:555)](Platforms\Oculus\HowTo\StandingCamera\HT_Rift_Camera_Setup_10.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. In the Blueprint editor under the **Variables** section, create a new **Vector** variable called **CameraHeight** and set the **Z** value to **180**.

    ![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_03.png)

    [region:note]
    This number set in CameraHeight should be set to the real world standing height of the user in Centimeters.
    [/region]

1. Drag off the output of the Set Tracking Origin node and search for the **Set Relative Location** node, selecting the **SetRelativeLocation(VRCameraRoot)** option.

    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_04.png)(w:342)](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_04.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. Connect the **CameraHeight** variable to the **New Location** input on the Set Relative Location node and then press the Compile button. When completed your Event Graph should look like the following image.

    [REGION:fullwidth]
    [INCLUDE:Platforms\GearVR\HowTo\CameraSetup\#GearVRCamera]
    [/REGION]

    [region:tip]
    You can copy the completed Blueprint by clicking on the upper left-hand corner of above and pressing CRTL + C to copy the graph. Once copied, go to your Blueprints event and press CTRL + V to paste it in. 
    [/region]

1. Drag the **GearVR_Pawn** Blueprint from the Content Browser to a level, making sure that it is placed as close to the ground as possible.

    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_06.png)(w:555)](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_06.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. Select the GearVR_Pawn Blueprint and in the **Details** panel under the **Pawn** setting, set the **Auto Possess Player** from **Disabled** to **Player 0**.

    [REGION:lightbox]
    [![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_07.png)(w:181)](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_07.png)
    [/REGION]

    [REGION:caption]
    Click for full image.
    [/REGION]

1. Finally, go to the **Main Toolbar** and click on the small white triangle next to **Launch Options** and then select your Android device from the list to start the packaging and deployment to that device.

    ![](HT_GearVR_Camera_Setup_08.png)

1. Once the UE4 project has deployed, put your Smartphone into your Gear VR HMD and when you move your head around it should look like the following video. 

